1 (2) offering an upfront incentive or rebate under § 7–1006 of this subtitle.
2 (b) NOTWITHSTANDING ANY PROVISION OF THIS SUBTITLE, IF THE
3 COMMISSION DETERMINES THAT THE COSTS LISTED IN SUBSECTION (A) OF THIS
4 SECTION ARE CONSISTENT WITH THE GOALS OF §§ 7–1005 AND 7–1006 OF THIS
5 SUBTITLE, THE COMMISSION SHALL APPROVE THE USE OF REGULATORY ASSET
6 ACCOUNTING IN RECOVERING THE COSTS.
7 (C) To the extent feasible, the costs listed in subsection (a) of this section shall be
8 recovered by the investor–owned electric company within the calendar year in which those
9 costs were incurred.
10 [(c)] (D) Notwithstanding any provision of this subtitle, an investor–owned
11 electric company may pursue and use a performance incentive mechanism to cover the cost
12 of using distributed energy resources or an aggregator of distributed ENERGY resources
13 under this subtitle.
14 SECTION 2. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That:
15 (a) The General Assembly finds that the use of distributed energy storage in the
16 State would provide reliability and electric system benefits in Maryland.
17 (b) By January 1, 2026, the Public Service Commission shall evaluate programs
18 enacted in other states to facilitate the installation of energy storage within homes and
19 businesses.
20 (c) After completing the evaluation required under subsection (b) of this section,
21 the Commission shall coordinate with electric companies and other stakeholders to design,
22 by June 1, 2026, programs to advance and expand home– and business–sited energy storage
23 in the State.
24 SECTION 2. 3. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That this Act shall take effect
25 October 1, 2025.
